[Event "Soviet Championship"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1959.??.??"]
[EventDate "?"]
[Round "?"]
[Result "1-0"]
[White "Leonid Alexandrovich Shamkovich"]
[Black "Viktor Savelievich Zheliandinov"]
[ECO "A66"]
[WhiteElo "?"]
[BlackElo "?"]
[PlyCount "39"]

1.d4 {Notes by Eric Schiller.} Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 e6 4.Nc3 exd5
5.cxd5 d6 6.e4 g6 7.f4 Qe7 {Black tries to avoid the main
lines of the Four Pawns Attack, which runs 7...Bg7 8.Bb5+!
This move was introduced in the present game and has been more
or less forgotten, for good reason. Shamkovich simply ignores
the threat on the e-pawn, daring Black to capture.} 8.Nf3 {!}
Nbd7 { 8...Nxe4 9.Qa4+! A simple fork, winning a piece.} 9.e5
{!} dxe5 10.fxe5 Nxe5 11.Bb5+ Ned7+ {A check parried by a
check! Does this resource save Black's bacon?} 12.Kf2 Ng4+
13.Kg3 {! The brave king runs onto the battlefield to
personally grapple with the knight, which must retreat.} Nge5
14.Nxe5 Qxe5+ 15.Bf4 Qf6 {Now White has the
initiative. Neither side has a castled king, though White need
only bring his rook to the e-file and then retreat the king to
g1. Shamkovich doesn't fall for the temptation of securing his
own king, and chooses the mighty queen, instead of the rook,
to challenge the enemy monarch.} 16.Qe2+ {!} Be7 17.d6 {!} g5
{? 17...Qh4+ 18.Kf3 a6 19.Bxd7+ Bxd7 20.Qxe7+ Qxe7 21.dxe7 is
about the best Black could have hoped for.} 18.Be5 {!} Bxd6
{The Black queen is safe, because of the pin on the b8-h2
diagonal. But the bishop hangs with check.} 19.Bxd6+ Kd8
20.Bc7+ {!} {A cute finish. Black resigned because after
capturing the bishop, he loses the queen to the knight fork at
d5.} 1-0

